Pour the @water{300%ml} for the rice into a #medium saucepan{} with a tight-fitting #lid{}.

Stir in the @Basmati Rice{150%g} and @salt{1/4%tsp}, then bring to the boil. Once boiling, turn
the heat down to medium and cover with the #lid{}.

Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave
to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook
in its own steam).

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @Garlic Clove{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Heat a drizzle of @?oil{} in a medium saucepan on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @Korma Curry Paste{50%g}, @Tomato Puree{30%g} and garlic. Cook, stirring,
until fragrant, ~{1%minute}.

Next, pour the @water{150%ml} for the sauce into the pan of spices.

Stir through the @Diced British Chicken Breast{240%g}, @Chicken Stock Paste{10%g} and
@Sugar{1%tsp}.

Bring to a boil, then lower the heat and simmer until the chicken is cooked through and
the sauce has thickened, ~{10-12%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging.
> It's cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Once thickened, stir through the @Peas{120%g}, @Creme Fraiche{75%g} and @Butter{20%g}.

Cook until the butter has melted and everything's piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Once the rice is cooked, use a #fork{} to fluff it up.

Add a splash of water to the curry if it's a little too thick. Season with @?salt{} and
@?pepper{} if needed.

Share the rice between your #bowls{} and spoon over the butter chicken.

Finish with a sprinkling of @Toasted Flaked Almonds{15%g}.

Enjoy!